title: For Sale:  USFA ZiP 22LR plus "suppressor barrel kit" and some extra parts
postcontent:
This is the weirdest looking gun you'll ever own, and it will be a great conversation piece at the range.

I bought the "suppressor barrel kit" which is NOT a barrel with an integral suppressor, and does not require a tax stamp. They should have called it a "threaded barrel kit". Supply your own suppressor.

This unit fell into the serial number range where the tolerances were known to be tight, and USFA shipped me a rebuild kit, which I installed. It made no noticeable difference in the function of the gun, but hey, extra parts are good, right? Now you don't have to buy the life extension kit.

I've put a few hundred rounds through this gun, and unless you use premium ammunition, it has stovepipes and feed jams, pretty much like most other small, lightweight .22lr semi-automatic pistols.

Will consider trade for a 9mm pistol or a Ruger SR22.

Face to face only, WA state ID required, concealed pistol license preferred.

title: For Sale/Trade:  USO SN12 3.5X combat optic with illuminated reticle
postcontent:
The USO SN12 Was developed for the USMC as a competitor for the ACOG. It features an incredibly ruged design with a 36mm tube diameter and a 26mm objective diameter. Unlike the ACOGs tritium lamp which must be replaced every so often, USO designed the SN12 with a battery illuminated reticle using a standard lithium button battery.  This iumination system has stood up to harsh testi g with out failure for years.  The SN12 was designed to take a beating with out damage or loss of zero (one reviewer chunked on across a parking lot repetitively and still managed incredibly accurate groups at 200+ yards. The USMC required a BDC calibrated to their spec loads and USO made a very easy to se system for them. Ultimately the SN12 was not chosen however a few managed to be marketed to the public.  



USO (US opticsis a relatively small operation who origonally set out to make high end shooting optics for the general public.  Lead times on their optics are notoriously long and they have a lo ve it or hate it reputation but always stand behind their products. 



My sell price is $800obo however I would be more than willing to trade for a quality pistol in 45acp, a decent rifle in 308, or bulk ammo in either 45, .223/5.56, or 30-'06.  I will also consconsider a 12ga Mossberg or benelli shotgun.  Other offers considered, the worst I can say is no.

postcontent:

Hornady XTP bullets were designed for hunting, self-defense, and law enforcement. One of the great things about the XTP bullet is reliable performance, it features controlled expansion where six serrations divide the bullet into six symmetrical sections. These sections weaken the jacket to allow controlled expansion at low velocities and ensures fragmentation does not occur at high velocities. The XTP bullet is really known for its stopping power. They were designed from the beginning to expand reliably at a variety of handgun velocities and deliver deep, terminal penetration with every shot. Most handgun bullets are designed to perform at a single factory-specified velocity where the XTP bullet is designed to offer controlled expansion over a range of velocities. 

Each XTP Bullet has a swaged core and drawn copper jacket to ensure uniform expansion and in-flight stability. Adding a cannelure to this bullet keeps the core and the jacket locked together while also allowing the cartridge case to tightly crimp, adding security at high velocities. This is not loaded ammunition.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1863 Civil War Musket
postcontent:
This has all the original parts and the initials of the solider who carried the gun carved into the stock. It does have its far share of ware but I am open to offers. Below is more information on the musket. 

The Model 1861 was the primary musket at the start of the Civil War.  Musket was designed as a single shot .58 cal. rifled muzzleloader featuring iron buttplate, "C" shaped hammer, bolster with clean out screw, two leaf sight, iron trigger guard, three flat barrel bands held in place with springs, two strap hooks on middle band and trigger guard, tulip head ramrod with bulged shank and threaded end, iron nose cap.  Springfield Armory supervised the manufacturing and distribution of the Model 1861 musket.  In order to fulfill shortages, production was sub-contracted to a number of private manufacturers, William Mason,  Taunton, Massachusetts, produced 30,000 muskets under the subcontract.  Lock is marked "1863" behind the hammer, with eagle and "US / WM. MASON. / TAUNTON." in front.  Barrel is marked "VP" over eagle head and "1863".  Buttplate is marked "US".  Three bands each marked "U". Cartouche in wood on left side indicates government inspection.  Barrel length 40in.

title: For Sale:  Polish PPS-43 Machine Gun Parts set Plus Receiver section and Trunnion
postcontent:
Have too many gun builds going on at the moment, so this one needs a new home.

This is an ATF saw cut, demilled, Polish PPS-43 submachinegun parts set. The PPS-43 is the wartime production model of the famous Soviet PPSH-41. It is constructed of almost all stamped and welded parts, and is one of the easier guns to rebuild into a functioning firearm. The PPS originally fired the potent 7.62x25 Tokarev round at over 900 rounds per minute. This gun, originally manufactured in Poland in the 1950's, has been cut through the receiver into pieces, and is no longer considered a firearm. Before it was cut it was in brand new, never fired condition. 

This package includes all parts needed to rebuild into a functioning gun, minus the barrel ($50 online) and a trunnion stabilizer ($5 online). Also included is what's called an 80% receiver that requires you to cut a few parts off of the metal, and drill some holes, and then weld it to the original receiver scraps. A Stenparts.com template is included so you can finish it in spec. Also included is one original 35 round magazine, unissued with a couple spots of surface rust.

ALL NFA AND GCA RULES APPLY! Rebuilding into a legal semi-automatic rifle or pistol will require shop equipment like a welder, grinder, drill press or dremel, etc. Although it is possible to complete one with a file, hand drill, scrap steel, a car battery, jumper cables, and a welding rod. It just takes more time.

There are many step-by-step instruction guides online for building these guns into legal shooters. I can not provide any instruction in the assembly of your gun. If you have a lot of experience as a machinist or gunsmith, this is an easy day-long job to rebuild into a semi-auto firearm. This is normally a full weekend job if you have the tools. Do your research and see what is involved in legally rebuilding parts kit guns, or buy it for the investment. These parts will only grow in value as guns are restricted in the future. Once completed, you have a legal semi-auto rifle or pistol with no serial number, and it's completely untraceable and legal to own. It's a really fun hobby for rainy weekends when you can't make it to the range.

I have over $220 in these parts. I'm selling this package for $175 through Paypal plus $20 shipping, or $165 in cash or trade. You can't find all of these components online for a lower price. I've checked. 

5% discount for NRA Members, just send proof of your membership via Email.

No ID or FFL required to purchase. 

I will accept trades for items below. I WILL ALSO ACCEPT PAYPAL AND SHIP to anywhere in the U.S. where high capacity magazines aren't banned, otherwise I will have to disassemble the magazine before I ship. Shipping is a flat $20 anywhere.

I would prefer to sell through Paypal and ship because it's more convenient for me, but if cash or trade is the only option we would have to arrange to meet at the Norpoint gun range in Arlington either in the evening or weekends.

Will trade for: Original GI M16 parts, AR Lower receivers, AR 20" Pencil barrel, an older 9 shot .22 Revolver, Military surplus bolt action rifles, 8mm Mauser, .223/5.56, 9mm ammo, cool old stuff, etc. What do you have?

Up for sale/trade is a pre-lawsuit GSG MP5PK imported through American Tactical Imports.

If you don't know about this lawsuit what happened was Heckler & Koch sued German Sport Guns and ATI because their line of GSGs were practically exact clones of the H&K MP5 (just in .22LR).
